Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat
oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{12%ounce} on a diagonal into ½-inch-thick pieces.
Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary.

In a #medium bowl{} (use a #large bowl{} for 4 servings), gently combine
@ground beef{10%ounce}, @panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, @garlic powder{1%tsp},
@salt{3/4%tsp}, and @pepper{}.

Form into two 1-inch-tall loaves (four loaves for 4).

Place meatloaves on one side of a lightly oiled #baking sheet{}. Toss carrots on
empty side with a large drizzle of @olive oil{}, salt, and pepper. Roast on top
rack until meatloaves are cooked through and carrots are browned and tender,
~{22-25%minutes}.

> TIP: Line sheet with foil first for easier cleanup.

> TIP: Love extra-crispy veggies? Once meatloaves are done, remove from sheet and
> continue roasting carrots for 2-3 minutes more.

While everything roasts, halve, peel, and thinly slice @onion{1}. Pick
@parsley{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems; roughly chop leaves.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large, preferably nonstick, pan{} over
medium-high heat. Add broccoli and a pinch of salt; cook, stirring occasionally,
until softened and lightly browned, ~{5-7%minutes} (7-10 minutes for 4
servings). Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Add a large drizzle of oil to same pan over medium-high heat. Add onion; cook,
stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{6-9%minutes}.

> TIP: Lower heat and add a splash of water if onion begins to brown too
> quickly.

Add @cream cheese{2%tbsp}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @water{1/2%cup},
and @sugar{3/4%tsp} to pan with onion; cook until thickened, ~{1-3%minutes} more.

Turn off heat; stir in @butter{1%tbsp} and a pinch of chopped parsley. Taste and
season with salt and pepper.

Carefully toss broccoli and carrots together with half the @sumac{1%tsp} (all for
4 servings).

Divide meatloaves and carrots and broccoli between plates. Spoon caramelized
onion sauce over meatloaves; garnish with remaining chopped parsley. Serve.

> Ground Meat is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.